Networks and Access

Carole Voulgaris

9/24/2021

In this tutorial, Ill be demonstrating how to calculate and visualize accessibility using the R5 routing engine developed by Conveyal.

Setup

The r5r package runs a Java application in the background, and youll need to have the Java SE Development Kit 11 installed on your computer for it to work. You can install it (for free) from Oracle here.

Youll also need to increase the amount of memory R will allocate to Java processes using options() before you load your libraries.

options(java.parameters = "-Xmx2G")

library(r5r)
library(osmextract)
library(tidyverse)
library(sf)
library(ggthemes)
library(ggspatial)
library(tigris)
library(wesanderson)
library(tidytransit)

Load networks

In this example, well be looking at access to schools in San Luis Obispo, California. Well need data on the transit network and the street network. The local transit agency is SLO Transit, and well get their data from their GTFS feed. The following code will create a folder called networks in your working directory, then download the transit network data and save it to that folder.

Note that you only need to run this code chunk once. If you already have a networks directory with a GTFS file in it, theres no need to run this code again.

dir.create("networks")

download.file("https://app.mecatran.com/urb/ws/feed/c2l0ZT1zbG90cmFuc2l0O2NsaWVudD1zZWxmO2V4cGlyZT07dHlwZT1ndGZzO2tleT0zZTMwMzM1OTRiMTE2NzA0N2IxNjQwNjA0ZjQwMGMzMzdiM2E1MTQ0", file.path("networks","SLOgtfs.zip"), mode = "wb", quiet=TRUE)

Now we need data on the street network. We can get that from OpenStreetMaps, using the osmextract package. Well use oe_match() to find a url for the San Luis Obispo street network. oe_match() will save a download url to the variable called SLO_file and print a message with the name of the provider.

SLO_file <- oe_match("San Luis Obispo")
## No exact match found for place = San Luis Obispo and provider = geofabrik. Best match is Manitoba. 
## Checking the other providers.
## An exact string match was found using provider = openstreetmap_fr.

Now, we can use oe_read() to both download the data to the networks folder and to read in a layer of lines representing the street network. The function will read all line features within the area (including rivers, for example), so well filter to only include lines that are maked as highways (all roads and even pedestrian paths are coded as highways in OpenStreetMap).

SLO_streets <- oe_read(SLO_file$url, 
                   provider = "openstreetmap_fr", 
                   download_directory = "networks", 
                   layer = "lines", 
                   quiet = TRUE) %>%
  filter(!is.na(highway))

Lets take a look at those streets by plotting a quick map.

ggplot(SLO_streets) +
  geom_sf()

Since Im familiar with the area, I can see that osmextract has returned the roads for all of San Luis Obsipo County, and Im really only interested in the City of San Luis Obispo.

Ill load a polygon of the city limits using the places() function from the tigris package. That returns the boundaries for all the census-designated places (including cities) in California, and Ill filter to keep just the one for San Luis Obispo. Ill use st_transform() to make sure the city limits polygon is in the same coordinate system as the streets layer.

Then Ill select only the streets within the city limits and create a new map of those. Note that this doesnt affect the network I downloaded and saved to my networks folder, which still includes all the roads in the whole county.

Ill project these in the California State Plane coordinate system (Zone 5). By using coord_sf() instead of st_transform(), Im only changing how the data are displayed the underlying data is still in latitude/longitude coordinates.

CA5_state_plane <- "+proj=lcc +lat_1=34.03333333333333 +lat_2=35.46666666666667 +lat_0=33.5 +lon_0=-118 +x_0=2000000 +y_0=500000 +ellps=GRS80 +units=m +no_defs"

SLO_city_limits <- places("California") %>%
  filter(NAME == "San Luis Obispo") %>%
  st_transform(crs = st_crs(SLO_streets))


SLO_streets <- SLO_streets[SLO_city_limits,]

ggplot(SLO_streets) +
  geom_sf() +
  coord_sf(crs = CA5_state_plane)

Load school locations

I can also use OpenStreetMaps to get the locations of all the schools in San Luis Obispo. Note that OpenStreetMaps is crowdsourced data, and all the information in there has been added by volunteers. Its a pretty good representation of the street network in much of the world (but not everywhere). The reliability of other data is not as good. To find all the features that can be available from OpenStreetMap, you can refer to the OpenStreemMap wiki here.

Ill read in all the points from OpenStreetMaps in San Luis Obispo County and keep only the ones labeled as schools. Ill also filter the data to only include points within the city limits.

The r5r package requires that point datasets have a column called id, so Im also renaming the osm_id column to be called id.

SLO_schools <- oe_read(SLO_file$url, 
                   provider = "openstreetmap_fr", 
                   download_directory = "networks", 
                   layer = "points", 
                   quiet = TRUE) %>%
  filter(str_detect(other_tags, '"amenity"=>"school"')) %>%
  st_filter(SLO_city_limits) %>%
  rename(id = osm_id)

ggplot(SLO_streets) +
  geom_sf(color = 'gray') +
  geom_sf(data = SLO_schools, color = "darkblue") +
  coord_sf(crs = CA5_state_plane)  +
  theme_void()

Set up grid of points

Well want to caculate the travel time from those schools to every other point in the city. To represent every point, Ill make a grid of points that covers the whole city. Im also going to create an ID column for that grid. In the st_make_grid() function, Im setting square = FALSE to create a hexagonal grid. If I were to leave that argument out, it would create a grid of squares.

Note that an alternative to creating a grid of points would be to use a set of points representing a set of small features that covers the study area reasonably well. Parcels or census blocks could work nicely.

Ill be using the grid to display the travel time values, but Ill use the centroids of the cells as the points to compute travel times to.

grid <- st_sf(st_make_grid(SLO_city_limits, 
                           square = FALSE, 
                           n = c(100,100),
                           what = "polygons")) %>%
  st_filter(SLO_city_limits) 

colnames(grid) <- "geometry"
st_geometry(grid) <- "geometry"

grid <- grid %>%
  mutate(id = seq(1, length(grid$geometry), by=1))

grid_points <- st_centroid(grid)

ggplot(grid) +
  geom_sf() +
  geom_sf(data = SLO_schools, color = "darkblue") +
  geom_sf(data = SLO_streets, alpha = 0.2) +
  coord_sf(crs = CA5_state_plane) + 
  theme_map()

Set up r5r core

Now well setup a network that incorporates both the transit network and the street network that are saved in the networks directory.

r5r_core <- setup_r5("networks", verbose = FALSE)

Calculate travel time matrix

Were going to calculate the travel time from each school to all the points in the grid. This is for transit (Im adding walking to allow people to walk up to 1000 meters to access a transit stop). Other options include BICYCLE and CAR.

This is based on the current transit schedules, so we need to indicate what day and time someone would be making this trip. Ive set it for my anniversary at 2pm.

ttm <- travel_time_matrix(r5r_core = r5r_core,
                          origins = SLO_schools,
                          destinations = grid_points,
                          mode = c("WALK", "TRANSIT"),
                          departure_datetime = as.POSIXct("15-11-2021 14:00:00",
                                 format = "%d-%m-%Y %H:%M:%S"),
                          max_walk_dist = 1000,
                          max_trip_duration = 480,
                          verbose = FALSE)

That created a data frame with a row for each combination of origins (schools) and destinations (points throughout the city), with three columns: one indicating the origin, one indicating the destination, and one indicating the travel time (by a combination of walking and transit) between those two points.

I can use pivot_wider() to reshape this data frame into one that has a row for each point in our grid and a column for each school.

Then I can merge that data frame to the grid points so I can show those travel times on the map. I want a map that represents the minimum travel time to any school, so Ill use mutate() to create a new column with the minimum travel time across all schools. The matrix has an NA value for trips that arent possible by transit (weve set the maximum travel time 4 hours). In order to caculate a minimum, well replace those NA values with 999. After merging the data, I need to specify that this is still spatial data be using st_geometry() to indicated which column has the spatial data.

tt_wide <- ttm %>%
  pivot_wider(names_from = fromId, 
              names_prefix = "from", values_from = travel_time) %>%
  rename(id = toId) %>% 
  merge(grid) %>%
  replace(is.na(.), 999) %>%
  rowwise() %>%
  mutate(from_any = min(c_across(starts_with("from")), na.rm = TRUE))

st_geometry(tt_wide) <- "geometry"

Now I can plot my grid on a map showing the continuous variation in travel time to a school for any point in the city.

ggplot(SLO_streets) +
  geom_sf(data = tt_wide, 
          aes(fill = from_any), 
          color = NA) +
  geom_sf(alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_fill_gradient2(low = "green", mid = "yellow", high = "red", 
                       midpoint = 30,
        name = "Transit Travel\ntime to the\nnearest school\n(minutes)") +
  coord_sf(crs = CA5_state_plane) +
  theme_map()

Create isochrones

I can create isochrones by subsetting the grid based on bins of travel time values and using st_union() to combine polygons within each bin into a single polygon.

iso_pallete <- wes_palette("Zissou1", n = 5)

iso10min <- tt_wide[tt_wide$from_any < 11,] %>%
  st_union()

iso20min <- tt_wide[tt_wide$from_any < 21,] %>%
  st_union()

iso30min <- tt_wide[tt_wide$from_any < 31,] %>%
  st_union()

ggplot(SLO_streets) +
  geom_sf(data = iso30min, 
          aes(fill = "Area within 30 minutes"), 
          color = NA) +
  geom_sf(data = iso20min, 
          aes(fill = "Area within 20 minutes"), 
          color = NA) +
  geom_sf(data = iso10min, 
          aes(fill = "Area within 10 minutes"), 
          color = NA) +
  geom_sf(alpha = 0.5) +
  scale_fill_manual(values = c(iso_pallete[1], 
                               iso_pallete[3],
                               iso_pallete[5]),
        name = "Transit Travel\ntime to the\nnearest school\n(minutes)") +
  coord_sf(crs = CA5_state_plane) +
  theme_map()

You can calcuate the areas of these polygons, and you can also use the methods you practiced in Assignment 3 to analyze whats located within them.

Calculate accessibility

When you have a lot of locations youre interested in, describing accessibility in terms of isochrones can get complicated because you end up with a lot of overlapping isochrones, and youre not as interested in whether theres an amenity with 10 minutes, but in how many you can reach within 10 minutes.

The r5r package also has a function called accessibility() thats useful for that type of question. Lets look at the bicycle accessiblity of transit stops.

Loading transit stop locations

Ive already saved the transit network (as a GTFS feed) to my networks folder, and I can use the tidytransit package to extract the locations of all the transit stops.

The read_gtfs() function reads in all the data describing transit routes, stops and schedules. Ill save that data into an object called SLO_transit, which includes a data frame with details about each stop, including its latitude and longitude coordinates. Well use st_as_sf() to convert that to a points layer with the same coordinate reference system as the grid we created previously.

SLO_transit <- read_gtfs(file.path("networks", "SLOgtfs.zip"))

transit_stops <- st_as_sf(SLO_transit$stops, 
                          coords = c("stop_lon", "stop_lat"), 
                          crs =st_crs(grid))

Set up grid of points with stops data

Now, well count how many transit stops are within each grid cell and create a new set of grid points that includes an attribute indicating how many transit stops are in each grid cell.

Im using as.character() to force R to treat the number of stops as a discrete variable (since there are only three possible values) rather than a continuous variable.

transit_grid <- grid %>%
  mutate(num_stops = lengths(st_covers(grid, transit_stops)))

transit_points <- st_centroid(transit_grid)

ggplot(transit_points) +
  geom_sf(aes(color = as.character(num_stops))) +
  scale_color_manual(values = c("gray", "cornsilk", "lightgreen"), 
                    name = "Number of\ntransit stops") +
  theme_void()

Calculate accessibility

Now Ill calculate the accessibilty. By using a step decay function with a cutoff of 11 and the mode set to "WALK", Im specifying that I want to know the number of transit stops with a ten-minute walk from each point in the grid.

I can join the result to my orginal grid to show the results on a map.

transit_access <- accessibility(r5r_core,
                        origins = transit_points,
                        destinations = transit_points,
                        mode = "WALK",
                        opportunities_colname = "num_stops",
                        decay_function = "step",
                        cutoffs = 11,
                        departure_datetime = as.POSIXct("15-11-2021 14:00:00",
                                 format = "%d-%m-%Y %H:%M:%S"),
                        max_walk_dist = 500,
                        time_window = 60,
                        percentiles = 50,
                        verbose = FALSE) %>%
  mutate(id = as.numeric(from_id)) %>%
  merge(grid)

st_geometry(transit_access) <- "geometry"

ggplot(transit_access) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = accessibility), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(name = "Transit stops\nwithin 10-minutes\nwalk") +
  coord_sf(crs = CA5_state_plane) +
  theme_void()

One thing about a step decay function is that it implies that someone who lives 19 minutes from a transit stop has access and someone who lives 21 minutes from that stop has no access. You can also use a continuous decay function that assumes everyone in the study area has some degree of access to all the stops, but they have less access to the ones that are further away.

One possible continuous function available in the accessibility() function is the half-life exponential function ("exponential"). When we use theis function with a cutoff value of 5 minutes, it implies that accessibility decreases exponentially with distance, and will decrease by one-half for every five minutes.

transit_access2 <- accessibility(r5r_core,
                        origins = transit_points,
                        destinations = transit_points,
                        mode = "WALK",
                        opportunities_colname = "num_stops",
                        decay_function = "exponential",
                        cutoffs = 5,
                        departure_datetime = as.POSIXct("15-11-2021 14:00:00",
                                 format = "%d-%m-%Y %H:%M:%S"),
                        max_walk_dist = 500,
                        time_window = 60,
                        percentiles = 50,
                        verbose = FALSE) %>%
  mutate(id = as.numeric(from_id)) %>%
  merge(grid)

st_geometry(transit_access2) <- "geometry"

ggplot(transit_access2) +
  geom_sf(aes(fill = accessibility), color = NA) +
  scale_fill_viridis_c(name = "Accessiblity score") +
  coord_sf(crs = CA5_state_plane) +
  theme_void()

The R5 core has been running in the background this whole time and using a lot of memory. Before wrap up, lets turn it off.

stop_r5(r5r_core)
## r5r_core has been successfully stopped.
rJava::.jgc(R.gc = TRUE)

Im also going to save that grid of accessibility values for use in the next assignment.

st_write(transit_access2, 'SLO_access.geojson', append=FALSE, quiet=TRUE )
